% -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section*{Summary of Pre-Registered Results}
Table~\ref{table:preregresults} summarizes the pre-registered intent-to-treat (ITT) estimates pooled across all four Wikipedia language communities. These are the primary confirmatory analyses described in the main text: the effect of being assigned to receive thanks on (1) the number of thanks subsequently sent to other editors, (2) two-week retention on Wikipedia, (3) post-treatment labor hours per day among newcomers, and (4) a manipulation check confirming that treated participants recalled receiving thanks in a follow-up survey. All p-values except the manipulation check are adjusted for multiple comparisons using the Holm method.


% -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section*{Machine Learning Models for Participant Selection}
As described in the main text, volunteers used a custom software application (Figure~\ref{fig:app}) to identify and thank Wikipedia contributors whose recent edits were flagged as good-faith contributions by machine learning models maintained by the Wikimedia Foundation. Table~\ref{table:mlresults} reports the precision and recall of these models on held-out test data. High precision ensures that nearly all flagged edits were genuinely good-faith, while high recall ensures that few deserving edits were missed. German Wikipedia was excluded because we did not use machine learning method for participant selection of this community.


% -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

\section*{Randomization Balance}
To confirm that the block randomization successfully created comparable treatment and control groups, Table~\ref{table:balance} compares pre-treatment characteristics across all participants. Randomization was stratified by language and experience level, so categorical variables (experience category, newcomer status, and language) are perfectly balanced by design. For continuous pre-treatment variables---labor hours per day, total labor hours, thanks sent, and thanks received---we report Wilcoxon rank-sum tests and standardized differences (Cohen's $d$). With over 15,000 participants, even trivially small differences can reach statistical significance; the key diagnostic is that all standardized differences are below $|d| = 0.05$, indicating negligible imbalance.


% -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section*{Robustness to Participant Exclusions}
During the study, 142 randomization blocks (284 participants) were excluded from the primary analysis because one or both members of a block had deleted their account or received multiple thanks due to software errors or volunteer selection decisions. Table~\ref{table:predrop_results} compares the ITT estimates before and after these exclusions. The consistency of point estimates, standard errors, and p-values across the two samples confirms that the exclusions do not materially affect the conclusions reported in the main text.


% -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
% Full model results

\section*{Full Intent-to-Treat Results by Subgroup and Language}
The paper reports pooled treatment effects and highlights key subgroup differences between newcomers and experienced contributors. Tables~\ref{table:full_itt_subgroup} and~\ref{table:full_itt_language} present the complete ITT estimates. Table~\ref{table:full_itt_subgroup} breaks results down by participant experience level (all participants, newcomers, and experienced contributors), pooled across languages. Table~\ref{table:full_itt_language} reports language-specific estimates for each Wikipedia community, enabling readers to assess the consistency of treatment effects across the four cultural and linguistic contexts.


% -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

\section*{Labor Hours Interaction Models}
The main text reports that receiving thanks increased post-treatment labor hours per day. Table~\ref{table:full_labor_perday} presents the full coefficient estimates from Tweedie generalized linear mixed models with a log link, including the intercept, main treatment effect, pre-treatment labor hours, and their interaction. Random intercepts for randomization blocks account for the paired design. Percentage changes are computed as $(e^{\hat{\beta}} - 1) \times 100$ to aid interpretation on the original scale. As reported in the Exploratory Subgroup Analysis section below, the treatment effect on labor hours varies by pre-treatment activity level, with opposing interaction patterns for newcomers and experienced contributors (Figure~\ref{fig:labor.hours.interaction}).


% -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

% -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

\section*{Exploratory Subgroup Analysis: Labor Hours Interaction by Experience Level}
As a follow-up exploratory analysis not included in the pre-registration, we investigated whether the treatment effect on post-treatment labor hours varied by pre-treatment activity level and differed between newcomers and experienced contributors. We conducted a stepwise analysis of three Tweedie generalized linear mixed models: (1) a baseline model with treatment assignment only, (2) a model adjusting for centered pre-treatment labor hours per day as a covariate, and (3) an interaction model allowing the treatment effect to vary by pre-treatment activity level. We conducted these analyses separately for newcomers (accounts $<$90 days old) and experienced contributors, re-centering covariates within each subgroup to estimate subgroup-specific effects. Each model includes random intercepts for the matched-pair design. Model selection using Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) weights \cite{burnham_model_2002} consistently favored the interaction model (AIC weights $>$0.99 for all comparisons). Model diagnostics using simulated residuals \cite{hartig_dharma_2022} are presented in Figure~\ref{fig:tweedie_dharma}. Full coefficient estimates are in Table~\ref{table:full_labor_perday}; Figure~\ref{fig:labor.hours.interaction} shows the marginal treatment effects by pre-treatment activity level for each subgroup.

The interaction with pre-treatment activity differed in direction across experience groups. For newcomers, the average treatment effect was large and positive but diminished for those with higher pre-treatment activity. For experienced contributors, no average treatment effect was found, but the interaction was positive---higher pre-treatment activity amplified the treatment effect. These opposing patterns are consistent with the discussion in the main text: gratitude may function as a self-efficacy signal for new contributors entering the community, and as a reinforcement mechanism for experienced contributors already embedded in high-output work patterns.


% -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

\section*{Validation of Model Assumptions}
We assessed the adequacy of all parametric models reported in the main text using simulation-based residual diagnostics implemented in the DHARMa package for R \cite{hartig_dharma_2022}. DHARMa creates randomized quantile residuals by simulating new data from the fitted model and comparing observed values against the simulated distribution. If the model is correctly specified, these residuals follow a uniform distribution on $[0,1]$, regardless of the underlying model family. This approach enables standard diagnostic plots---quantile-quantile (QQ) plots and residual-versus-predicted plots---to be applied uniformly to generalized linear models and generalized linear mixed models, including zero-inflated and over-dispersed count models.

For each model, we generated 1{,}000 simulations and performed a Kolmogorov-Smirnov (KS) test for uniformity, a dispersion test comparing the standard deviation of observed versus simulated residuals, and a zero-inflation test comparing the observed proportion of zeros to the simulated expectation. In addition, we present a normal QQ plot of residuals from the pre-registered difference-in-means specification for labor hours to motivate the switch to the Tweedie generalized linear mixed model, as described in the main text \cite{brooks_glmmtmb_2017}. Figures~\ref{fig:negbin_dharma}, \ref{fig:dim_qq}, and~\ref{fig:tweedie_dharma} present the residual diagnostic plots for each model.


% -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section*{Descriptive Statistics for Distribution of Thanks}
Table~\ref{table:thanks-distribution} reports the distribution of thanks by group, Wikipedia language edition, and participant experience level. Figures~\ref{fig:first-gen-thanks},~\ref{fig:second-gen-thanks},~\ref{fig:control-thanks}, and~\ref{fig:treated-vs-control-thanks} show the weekly time series of first-generation thanks received, second-generation thanks sent by treated participants, thanks sent by control participants, and a direct comparison of treated versus control thanking behavior, respectively. Because participants were recruited in rolling waves, the calendar-date patterns in these figures reflect recruitment timing rather than treatment timing; apparent temporal differences between groups should not be interpreted as onset-lag effects. See Table~\ref{table:second-gen-sent} for within-pair onset-lag comparisons that account for this design feature.


% -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section*{Second-Generation Thanks: Sender Behavior and Response Lag}
Both treated and control participants sent second-generation thanks, but treated participants sent 43\% more overall (1{,}504 vs.\ 1{,}048). Because participants were recruited in rolling waves throughout the study period, absolute calendar dates of thanking are not meaningful for comparing groups. Instead, we measure the \emph{onset lag}: the number of days from a shared pair-level baseline to the date each participant sent their first second-generation thanks, with one observation per unique sender. The baseline is the date on which the volunteer application sent first-generation thanks to the treated participant in each matched pair. Both the treated participant and their matched control use this same date as their baseline, making the comparison within-pair and directly comparable.

Table~\ref{table:second-gen-sent} reports the volume, intensity, and onset timing of second-generation thanks sent by each group. The median onset lag was similar across groups: 15~days for treated versus 13~days for control overall. Within individual languages, onset lags were also comparable (11--16~days for both groups in every language). The treatment effect therefore operated primarily through increased volume and intensity of thanking---more unique senders (266 vs.\ 222), and more thanks per sender (5.7 vs.\ 4.7)---rather than through earlier initiation of thanking behavior.

% -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section*{Second-Generation Thanks: Recipient Patterns and Community Circulation}
Of the 2{,}552 second-generation thanks sent during the study period, 1{,}444 (56.6\%) were received by Wikipedia editors outside the study and 1{,}108 (43.4\%) were received by other study participants. Table~\ref{table:second-gen-received} provides a full cross-tabulation of second-generation thanks by sender group (treated vs.\ control) and recipient status (treated participant, control participant, or non-participant). The majority of thanks to study participants went to treated participants (891 of 1{,}108, 80.4\%), which is expected because the same volunteer application used to select treatment participants also flagged their edits as thankable.

Because the active editing communities are small relative to the number of study participants (Table~\ref{table:second-gen-community}), second-generation thanks circulated back to control group members who were not targeted by the intervention. This pattern is most evident in Persian and Polish Wikipedias. In Persian, control participants received 74 second-generation thanks---32 from treated senders and 42 from control senders, an almost even split. In Polish, control participants received 130 thanks---63 from treated senders and 67 from control senders, again near parity. Figure~\ref{fig:received-by-group} shows the weekly count of second-generation thanks \emph{received} by treated versus control study participants, and Figure~\ref{fig:control-received-by-sender} decomposes thanks received by control participants by sender group. These patterns are consistent with the limited recipient pool in smaller communities causing second-generation thanks to circulate back to control group members, regardless of who initiated the thanking behavior.

Table~\ref{table:second-gen-community} contextualizes second-generation thanks within each language community. The communities vary substantially in size, from ${\sim}960$ monthly active editors in Arabic Wikipedia to ${\sim}6{,}350$ in German Wikipedia, while study participants often exceed the monthly active editor count (e.g., 4{,}528 participants vs.\ 1{,}462 active editors in Polish). Standardizing by community size reveals a striking contrast: Polish Wikipedia had 893 second-generation thanks per 1{,}000 active editors and Persian 570, versus only 95 in Arabic and 64 in German. German Wikipedia, despite its much larger active editor population, had the highest number of non-participant recipients (237), suggesting that second-generation thanks were predominantly directed outward to editors beyond the study. Polish Wikipedia had the broadest thanking spread at 4.2 recipients per sender, compared to 1.4--1.9 in all other languages.

% -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section*{Spillover Sensitivity Analysis}

The descriptive analyses above reveal that second-generation thanks sometimes circulated from treated participants back to control participants, potentially inflating control-group outcomes and attenuating the intent-to-treat (ITT) estimate. We assess this concern using three complementary analyses.

\paragraph{Contamination rate.} Not all participants assigned to the treatment arm actually received first-generation thanks: some cases were skipped by volunteers, expired before any volunteer reviewed them, or involved accounts deleted before thanks could be sent. Only second-generation thanks sent by participants with a verified first-generation thanks receipt (i.e., those with a non-null volunteer sender recorded in the data) constitute a genuine treatment-spillover pathway. Of the 104 second-generation thanks directed by treatment recipients toward control recipients (Table~\ref{table:second-gen-received}), 71 came from verified treated participants. These 71 thanks reached \textbf{49 unique control participants} (0.6\% of all controls; Table~\ref{table:second-gen-received}, parenthetical values). Contamination was negligible in Arabic (3 unique, 0.2\%) and German (5 unique, 0.2\%), but modest in Persian (4 unique, 0.3\%) and Polish (37 unique, 1.6\%).

\paragraph{Exposure response.} Among control participants, those who received at least one second-generation thank from a verified treated sender sent second-generation thanks themselves at a rate of 24.5\%, compared with 2.7\% among unexposed controls. This comparison is correlational rather than causal: exposed controls are likely more active editors who would send thanks regardless of exposure. Nonetheless, the magnitude is consistent with a spillover pathway.

\paragraph{Purified ITT.} Excluding the 49 exposed control participants from the control group yields a purified risk difference of 0.71 percentage points (treated sending rate 3.45\% vs.\ unexposed-control rate 2.74\%), compared with the standard ITT risk difference of 0.57 percentage points (3.45\% vs.\ 2.88\%). This 24\% increase in the estimated effect indicates that spillover to controls modestly attenuated the standard ITT estimate. The true direct effect of receiving first-generation thanks on second-generation thanks sending is somewhat larger than the reported ITT suggests.

\paragraph{Ecological pattern.} The four language communities differ substantially in their ratio of study participants to monthly active editors (Table~\ref{table:second-gen-community}): German Wikipedia is under-saturated (0.84 participants per active editor), while Polish and Arabic are highly saturated ($\sim$3.1 and 3.2). Consistent with the spillover hypothesis, German, the community least saturated by study participants, shows the largest treated-to-control sending ratio (266 vs.\ 139 thanks, ratio 1.91), while Persian and Polish show smaller ratios (1.36 and 1.41). Arabic is anomalous in that the control group marginally exceeded the treated group in thanks sent, which likely reflects other community dynamics rather than saturation alone. With only four data points, this pattern is suggestive but not formally testable.

Together, these analyses indicate that spillover from verified treated participants to control participants was small (0.6\% of controls directly affected) but dense in Polish Wikipedia where community saturation was highest. The standard ITT estimate is conservative by approximately 24\%, where the treatment effect on second-generation thanks sending is likely modestly underestimated.

